every user is assigned a personal home direcotory /home/username
system identifies users with a user if (UID) 

the superuser (root) this user has unlimited power and access to every comand and file 
to use these power superuser need to use sudo command

su command (substitute user) open new shell window where you are logged as root so you can do everything but it increase risk to destroy system 
system know who is allowed to use sudo by configuration file /etc/sudoers 
to save better open this file with visudo

/etc/passwd in this file is stored mapping between usernames and UIDs
200~root:x:0:0:root:/root:/bin/bash
this is the first line in this file lets understand this structure
1root - username
2	x - means password but real password is in /etc/shadowfile 
	* - means means the account is locked and cannot be used for login 
	a blank field means the user has not have password
3 a user id the root always have 0
4 group id - the numerical identifier for the user's primary group
5 gecos field - ahte additioinal informations abaut the user like number name...
6 home directory /root
7 deafult shell 

in this file are non-human users too like daemons who have limited permisions
to edit this file are recomended useradd usermod userdel commends


/etc/shadow in this file are stored sensitive user authentication information 
you can see what is in this file by using
sudo cat /etc/shadow
the file structure
root:MyEPTEa$6Nonsense:15000:0:99999:7:::
1 username
2 encrypted password 
3 date of last password change
4 minimum password age
5 maximum pasword age
6 password warning period
7 password inactivity period 
8 account expiration date
9 reserved fiels

/etc/group this dile defines the groups on the system and their members
witch group can have specific permisions to fules and directories
group informations 
cat /etc/group
root:*:0:pete
1 group name
3 group password
3 group id
4 list od users

user managment tools

adding user 
sudo useradd bob

removing user 
sudo userdel bob

changing passwords 
passwd bob
